00:00:28.750 --> 00:00:32.270
PROFESSOR: As it turns out, not
by coincidence, the Apollo

00:00:32.270 --> 00:00:35.950
program that started after
Kennedy's speech was made up

00:00:35.950 --> 00:00:38.270
of a few different elements of
things that had been sort of

00:00:38.270 --> 00:00:40.590
percolating in the background.

00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:44.490
And one of them was studies at
MIT on guidance, not so much

00:00:44.490 --> 00:00:48.290
to the Moon, but to Mars, and
coming out of Draper's

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:48.960
laboratories.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:53.290
So I wanted to say a little bit
about that story, because

00:00:53.290 --> 00:00:54.290
it's an interesting story.

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:55.970
And it's one you may not have
seen quite in this way.

00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:58.530
So what we've talked about
before and the inertial

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:00.150
guidance and all that
sort of stuff.

00:01:00.150 --> 00:01:03.990
This is the sort of very clearly
posed paradigmatic

00:01:03.990 --> 00:01:05.240
picture of him.

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:10.510
And during the Second World War,
they started making these

00:01:10.510 --> 00:01:11.010
gun sights.

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:12.860
And one of them was called
Doc's Shoebox.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:15.320
And then I think we talked about
that too, which allowed

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:16.930
him to sort of lead
the target.

00:01:16.930 --> 00:01:20.300
You can actually see, if you
go into the front door of

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:23.190
Draper Laboratories, they have
this prototype that he built

00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:26.740
in his garage, sitting there.

00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:28.610
And then during the war,
as we talked about--

00:01:28.610 --> 00:01:32.590
sorry, during the Cold War,
they built a lot of

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:33.380
different kinds of--

00:01:33.380 --> 00:01:34.740
I'm going to skip
through these--

00:01:34.740 --> 00:01:37.570
inertial guidance and
stuff, particularly

00:01:37.570 --> 00:01:39.210
for ballistic missiles.

00:01:39.210 --> 00:01:44.155
And a bunch of these guys,
including this guy here, Dick

00:01:44.155 --> 00:01:49.190
Batten, really did some
fundamental work in the theory

00:01:49.190 --> 00:01:51.740
of inertia guidance.

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:55.980
It was pretty much literally how
do I get a nuclear missile

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:59.850
to land on a Russian city, given
the gravity field of the

00:01:59.850 --> 00:02:02.260
Earth is not uniform, and
there's a lot of calculations,

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:04.650
and we don't have a lot
of different things?

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:06.210
And then this group--

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:09.430
the guy on the left, his name
is Hal Laning and he was a

00:02:09.430 --> 00:02:11.630
computer guy from the
Whirlwind group.

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:15.490
Milt Trageser is the guy in the
back there and Dick Batten

00:02:15.490 --> 00:02:16.190
is on the right.

00:02:16.190 --> 00:02:19.560
Batten actually still teaches
a course in Core 16 on

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:20.940
astronomical guidance.

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:23.000
Actually, he may not have
taught it this year.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:24.450
That's more or less a course
he's been teaching

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:29.060
continuously since
1945 or so, 1946.

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:33.360
And if you've ever seen when
they send a probe-- actually

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:37.390
they just did this with the
Messenger probe to Mercury--

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:43.040
and then they sort of swing it
around another planet as a way

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:45.690
to get it accelerated toward its
goal, as opposed to just

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:47.635
sending it directly there,
that's actually an idea that

00:02:47.635 --> 00:02:49.110
Batten invented.

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:53.010
It is now used commonly in all
these different space probes.

00:02:53.010 --> 00:02:55.040
And they made this Mars probe.

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:57.740
And the idea behind this probe
was to go to Mars, take one

00:02:57.740 --> 00:03:00.630
picture, and come back to
the Earth and reenter

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:01.890
and drop the film.

00:03:01.890 --> 00:03:05.130
And this thing, which looks just
like the Mercury capsule,

00:03:05.130 --> 00:03:06.740
is the film canister.

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:13.590
And they had also in the '50s,
they built the guidance system

00:03:13.590 --> 00:03:17.080
for the Polaris missile.

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:19.630
And the important thing about
the Polaris missile is it was

00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:21.890
the first missile that could
be launched out of a

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:24.210
submarine, out of the
Polaris submarine.

00:03:24.210 --> 00:03:29.640
And was a major US, huge project
during the '50s.

00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:34.110
And basically they wrote a very
short proposal, proposing

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:38.150
to use that guidance system
to go to the Moon.

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:41.730
And they were awarded a contract
August 4, I believe

00:03:41.730 --> 00:03:43.120
it was, 1961.

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:46.100
It was the first contract of the
entire Apollo program and

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:47.350
it came to MIT.

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:54.920
Which is some indicator a, of
how important they considered

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:55.570
the guidance.

00:03:55.570 --> 00:03:58.070
Like how do you get there and
how you keep from smashing

00:03:58.070 --> 00:03:59.360
into the Moon, and how do you
get home and keep from

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:02.010
smashing into the Earth
when you get home?

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:07.800
And b, it was the only major
contract of the entire program

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:09.290
that was awarded to
a university,

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:11.940
and not to a company.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:14.250
And of course, the president
was from Massachusetts.

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:20.790
One of the very senior technical
people, Bob Siemens,

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:23.040
was an MIT guy, a student
of Draper's.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:25.560
He was essentially the chief
engineer at this point.

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:28.710
And a little bit like the
Radiation Lab, there's no

00:04:28.710 --> 00:04:33.980
question that those influences
helped steer this contract,

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:35.580
which was a lot of money.

00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:37.520
Although it was less significant
for the money in

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:39.050
some sense, than for
the prestige that

00:04:39.050 --> 00:04:40.020
went along with it.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:41.420
And it was sole source.

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:42.370
There was no competition.

00:04:42.370 --> 00:04:43.260
There was no proposals.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:44.840
It just came straight MIT.

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:48.760
And all kinds of companies
protested it to Congress.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:51.120
And it turned out it was
fully legal, so they

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:54.920
never changed it.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:56.760
But it was not for a
computer, actually.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.360
It was just for this guidance
unit and it was over the

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:00.420
course of the project.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:09.070
And remember, this is 1961 and
all they thought about was how

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:10.620
do we get there and back?

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:15.560
And they begin working on this
problem in seven years or so.

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.520
And the idea was that
the astronaut would

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:19.290
sit inside the capsule.

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:25.180
And if you looked at the stars
with the telescope, you could

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:29.000
basically align yourself and
align the inertia platform.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.580
Remember the inertial platform
navigates with accelerometers,

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:33.940
which can be very accurate.

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:37.300
But what's problem
with doing that?

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:38.860
It drifts.

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:41.370
So it loses its absolute
accuracy over time.

00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:44.610
So every once in while, you have
to realign it and retell

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:45.480
it where it is.

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:49.280
And you could align yourself by
just pointing at the stars

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:51.380
and knowing which way
is up, in what's

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:53.880
called an inertial frame.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:57.280
But if you wanted to actually
navigate, you had to do things

00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:58.690
or closer to the planet.

00:05:58.690 --> 00:06:00.240
So you could look at particular

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:02.110
points on the Earth.

00:06:02.110 --> 00:06:04.810
The obvious one, the easiest one
is measure the size of the

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:06.610
Earth, because as
you go further

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:07.365
away, it get's smaller.

00:06:07.365 --> 00:06:09.620
It turns out that's not a very
accurate measurement.

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:12.100
But it is one way to measure
where you are.

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:15.610
The most accurate way to
measure it is star

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:16.070
occultation.

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:19.270
So that if there's a star that
passes by the horizon, you

00:06:19.270 --> 00:06:22.650
note the timing of that star and
that gives you a very good

00:06:22.650 --> 00:06:23.790
sense of where you are.

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:26.470
So there's a whole variety of
things-- is anybody into

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:29.160
astronomy here?

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:30.230
I never was particularly.

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:32.670
But last year, my brother
brought me a telescope that

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:35.120
has one of these motorized
mounts on it, where you can

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:37.270
sort of tell it what star it
is and it'll go there.

00:06:37.270 --> 00:06:40.770
That's basically what the Apollo
guidance computer was,

00:06:40.770 --> 00:06:42.990
where it would point out
different stars.

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:44.500
It had a little database.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:47.580
And the database of stars that
was used in the entire Apollo

00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:50.710
program was, I forget, something
like 100 stars long.

00:06:50.710 --> 00:06:54.230
And it was one junior engineer
in 1962, came to the MIT

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:56.990
libraries and looked up all the
star coordinates and put

00:06:56.990 --> 00:06:57.650
them in the computer.

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:00.760
And that's the one they used
all the way through.

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:03.850
And astronauts were then trained
to know which stars,

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:05.610
and they each had a number on
them, and they could align

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:10.460
themselves with the catalog
and make sure they were

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:12.040
getting there.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:15.900
And eventually, they ended up
putting a digital computer in

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:18.900
it, which was a pretty radical
step at the time.

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:21.990
Because again, computers
were room-size things.

00:07:21.990 --> 00:07:25.080
And this was a computer that
was briefcase size.

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:27.540
And for those of you who are
into computers, it looked a

00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:30.570
lot more like a microcontroller
than a

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:32.470
full-up, general purpose
computer.

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:36.680
It was modest numerical
capability, but lots of I/O

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:40.530
and interrupts and things going
in and out, 16 bits.

00:07:40.530 --> 00:07:43.440
And it wasn't actually a single
chip thing, like a

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:45.810
microcontroller today, but
it had a lot of those

00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:51.000
characteristics, including this
interface for the crew.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.580
And it tied into the
inertial system.

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:56.560
So you have this combination
of the gyroscopes, the

00:07:56.560 --> 00:08:01.180
telescopes, the computer itself,
and this display

00:08:01.180 --> 00:08:03.560
keyboard unit.

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:06.620
And this is--

00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:08.870
actually I forget who this is.

00:08:08.870 --> 00:08:10.790
I think it's Jim Lovell.

00:08:10.790 --> 00:08:12.360
No, Jim Lovell's the next one.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:15.170
One of the Apollo astronauts
operating this system.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:19.290
And there would have been a
display keyboard like that, up

00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:22.480
on the main console, which he's
looking at, you can see

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:23.320
at the top.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:24.080
I don't know if you're
familiar.

00:08:24.080 --> 00:08:27.430
Has anybody seen the Apollo
capsules down in the

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:31.080
Smithsonian Air and
Space Museum?

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:32.500
They looked very awkward
on Earth.

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:35.580
But they were easier in space,
where when they're launching,

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:38.220
this guy, he would be in the
launch position, and have his

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:41.470
back on the ground, looking
at this control panel.

00:08:41.470 --> 00:08:43.539
And then when they get
into space, he

00:08:43.539 --> 00:08:45.080
actually can move up here.

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:48.460
And this is actually 90 degrees
from that position.

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:51.300
And there's a whole station
where they navigate from.

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:57.420
And what they would do would
be navigate by--

00:08:57.420 --> 00:09:00.140
again, they're not flying the
spaceship doing this.

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:02.750
They're just aligning
the inertial system.

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:08.340
And then once the inertial
system knows where it's going,

00:09:08.340 --> 00:09:11.160
they type in where they want
to go on the keyboard.

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:16.930
And so every few hours or so,
the inertial system would need

00:09:16.930 --> 00:09:17.690
to be realigned.

00:09:17.690 --> 00:09:20.620
So it would point at where
it thinks the star was.

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:22.660
The astronaut would look through
these telescopes.

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:25.360
One was a sort of low power, for
getting the thing in the

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:25.910
field of view.

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:28.300
And one was a high power, for
the precision pointing.

00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:30.120
And then he had these
two little sets of

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:31.390
toggle switches here.

00:09:31.390 --> 00:09:35.840
One of them would just move the
mirror in one axis and the

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:37.830
other would actually rotate
the spacecraft around.

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:41.330
And between those two things,
they would realign the star.

00:09:41.330 --> 00:09:43.600
It would usually be off center,
just a little bit.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:45.100
And they would say no, that's
not where it should be.

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:46.390
It should be here.

00:09:46.390 --> 00:09:48.790
And then enter it into
the computer

00:09:48.790 --> 00:09:49.860
and say that's centered.

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:52.550
And the computer would take
those error corrections, in

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.080
what today we call
a common filter--

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:55.130
Batten was one of the inventors

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:57.180
of the common filter--

00:09:57.180 --> 00:09:59.835
and then update its
guidance solution.

00:09:59.835 --> 00:10:04.120
It turned out you could do
that very accurately in

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:05.270
getting to the Moon.

00:10:05.270 --> 00:10:08.880
And in Apollo 8, this is Jim
Lovell, who is probably best

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:12.480
known for his commanding of
Apollo 13, a few years later.

00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:14.490
But this is Apollo 8, where they
first flew to the Moon.

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:15.900
And here you can see
him doing it.

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:18.690
And there's the keyboard
unit up there.

00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:21.950
And there was essentially no
real hands-on of the joystick,

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:23.290
flying to the Moon.

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:25.850
It was much more OK, we've
got our unit aligned.

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:29.300
He did this 200 times over the
course of the trip to and from

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:30.810
the Moon on Apollo 8.

00:10:30.810 --> 00:10:34.170
This is where they orbited,
but they never landed.

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:41.440
And he realigned it 200 times.

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:43.790
It had very, very accurate
navigation.

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:46.600
And the rest of it would be OK,
here's where we want to

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:48.920
go, here's the velocity
we want to achieve.

00:10:48.920 --> 00:10:52.330
And the computer would just
orient the spacecraft, set up

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:54.880
the big thruster to fire, fire
it, and then have the big

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:56.720
velocity change.

00:10:56.720 --> 00:10:59.280
A bit change in how the
astronauts expected

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:00.606
to fly to the Moon.

00:11:00.606 --> 00:11:01.538
Yeah, Sarah?

00:11:01.538 --> 00:11:03.402
AUDIENCE: Is that a picture of
the Command Module or the

00:11:03.402 --> 00:11:04.340
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:06.180
PROFESSOR: This is in the
Command Module, actually.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:08.220
AUDIENCE: So there was
a DSKY in both?

00:11:08.220 --> 00:11:10.330
PROFESSOR: There was a
DSKY in both, yes.

00:11:10.330 --> 00:11:12.720
So there were two identical
copies of the computer, one

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:16.230
was in the Lunar Module and one
was in the Command Module.

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:19.100
They had different software
running on them though.

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:25.170
And in Apollo 13, that turned
out to be a huge benefit

00:11:25.170 --> 00:11:28.680
because they could shut the
entire Command Module down and

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:37.670
transfer the coordinates from
one to the other and keep the

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:40.780
inertial solution of where they
were in the Lunar Module,

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:42.370
while they powered down.

00:11:42.370 --> 00:11:45.460
So they had a redundant system
without really what being

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:47.780
aware of it, in a certain way,
without planning it, although

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:49.520
they did sort of plan it.

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:51.690
And the interesting thing is
these were two separate

00:11:51.690 --> 00:11:52.410
spacecrafts.

00:11:52.410 --> 00:11:53.830
How would you do that today?

00:11:53.830 --> 00:11:57.220
Well, you'd have some network
and you just say, copy the

00:11:57.220 --> 00:11:58.080
coordinates over.

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:00.290
And all they could do there
was read it off the LED

00:12:00.290 --> 00:12:03.820
display and yell it
down the tunnel.

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:05.700
And the other guy would
type it in.

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:06.700
There was no electrical

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:07.990
connection between two computers.

00:12:12.680 --> 00:12:16.610
This is actually-- the picture
in the MIT Museum, behind the

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:19.350
prototype of the computer
that's sitting there.

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.840
It's Davey Hoag, one of the
engineers on it, just another

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:22.620
view of it.

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:24.880
Although it's a very interesting
thing here, this

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:28.530
was the original block 1 version
of the computer.

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:30.520
And the idea was the astronauts
would be able to

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:32.500
repair the computer in flight.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:35.470
And it's sort of like, anybody
ever have an old IBM PC where

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:36.080
you could pull--

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:37.870
I guess PCs are still
this way.

00:12:37.870 --> 00:12:39.950
You can pull the cards
out and put new

00:12:39.950 --> 00:12:41.180
cards in them and stuff.

00:12:41.180 --> 00:12:42.100
That was the idea here.

00:12:42.100 --> 00:12:44.430
You'd be able to pull
the cards out.

00:12:44.430 --> 00:12:46.790
And they actually talked about
the astronauts having tools

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:49.060
and soldering irons and
things to repair

00:12:49.060 --> 00:12:51.750
the computer in flight.

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:57.220
That turned out to be a bad
idea because on a space

00:12:57.220 --> 00:13:00.360
flight, and this is still
true today, the physical

00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:03.180
environment becomes completely
contaminated with all of the

00:13:03.180 --> 00:13:05.880
exhalations from the
human bodies.

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:09.880
And on one of the Mercury
flights, one of the

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:11.840
electronics boxes shorted out.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:16.050
And it turned out there were
urine crystals from the

00:13:16.050 --> 00:13:18.070
astronaut that had--

00:13:18.070 --> 00:13:21.140
it was vapor I guess, that had
crystallized on the circuits

00:13:21.140 --> 00:13:22.020
and shorted them out.

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:25.990
And so after this, they ended
up going away from this

00:13:25.990 --> 00:13:28.640
in-flight repair and just
building one sealed box that

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:31.270
was completely hermetically
sealed, no possibility of

00:13:31.270 --> 00:13:32.240
repairing it.

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:34.670
And how did they have redundancy
you might ask?

00:13:34.670 --> 00:13:35.760
And the answer is they didn't.

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:37.840
They just tried to engineer
it really well, to

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:41.050
make it really reliable.

00:13:41.050 --> 00:13:44.520
Anybody know how many on the
Space Shuttle to control it?

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:46.170
Five.

00:13:46.170 --> 00:13:47.950
Five parallel redundant
computers.

00:13:47.950 --> 00:13:49.525
There's one in the
Apollo system.

00:13:49.525 --> 00:13:51.356
It never failed in flight.

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:56.670
This is another view
of that process.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:06.730
Here's where the astronaut in
the Command Module can look at

00:14:06.730 --> 00:14:08.630
