yet another one.

00:14:52.270 --> 00:14:54.970
This is actually a view that's
kind of interesting to look

00:14:54.970 --> 00:15:03.350
at, of the position error at the
critical moment where they

00:15:03.350 --> 00:15:06.920
left the Earth's gravitational
field and they entered the

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:08.690
Moon's gravitational field.

00:15:08.690 --> 00:15:14.190
And when they're sighting on
the Earth's horizon as they

00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:17.460
get that far away, the
error is just rising

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:19.100
and rising and rising.

00:15:19.100 --> 00:15:22.040
And then at this critical
moment, they switched and they

00:15:22.040 --> 00:15:26.970
sight on the lunar horizon
with these three stars.

00:15:26.970 --> 00:15:30.480
And you can see the error just
goes down almost to nothing,

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:33.720
compared to the later calculated
accurate value.

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:37.840
So they plotted this stuff
obsessively and

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:40.140
were extremely clear.

00:15:40.140 --> 00:15:41.450
Actually, this is the
actual error.

00:15:41.450 --> 00:15:47.040
That's the position of where
their orbit is and depending

00:15:47.040 --> 00:15:48.110
on where you are.

00:15:48.110 --> 00:15:50.890
And that was part of the common
filter problem is you

00:15:50.890 --> 00:15:52.700
only want to take the sightings
to update the

00:15:52.700 --> 00:15:55.110
solution when it's going to
really be better than the

00:15:55.110 --> 00:15:57.320
noise in the process to do it.

00:15:57.320 --> 00:15:59.520
And Batten was very good
at figuring out

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:01.410
when that would be.

