00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:33.800
readings for today.

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:37.590
It captures the sense that this
Apollo project was partly

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:39.660
a product of what was
really the '50s,

00:22:39.660 --> 00:22:42.200
kind of Cold War mentality.

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:45.770
And by the time it came to
fruition in the late '60s, was

00:22:45.770 --> 00:22:47.100
a whole different world.

00:22:47.100 --> 00:22:50.640
In fact, if you look at the
naming of the Apollo capsules,

00:22:50.640 --> 00:22:53.770
the first ones are called Eagle
and Colombia and these

00:22:53.770 --> 00:22:57.010
kind of super high-brow,
patriotic names.

00:22:57.010 --> 00:23:00.170
And then by the later Apollo
programs, the capsules are

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:03.760
called Snoopy and Aquarius,
and much more kind of

00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:07.240
reflecting '60s hippies
culture.

00:23:07.240 --> 00:23:12.900
And this guy Don Eyles, he
graduated from BU with a

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:16.310
degree in mathematics
in 1967, so two

00:23:16.310 --> 00:23:17.310
years before the landing.

00:23:17.310 --> 00:23:20.560
The Apollo program was already
beginning to wind down on the

00:23:20.560 --> 00:23:21.600
engineering.

00:23:21.600 --> 00:23:24.840
He got a job at Draper Labs and
he started working there.

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:27.310
And within a few months, he
was writing the code that

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:30.570
controlled the landing
on the Moon.

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:33.120
And most of the code was written
by him and a few other

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:35.950
people for the actual landing.

00:23:35.950 --> 00:23:39.360
And he was 24 years old when
Apollo 11 landed on the Moon.

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:40.450
And he was basically a hippie.

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:41.420
He had long hair.

00:23:41.420 --> 00:23:45.510
And he talks about, during his
lunch breaks, he would go out

00:23:45.510 --> 00:23:48.730
in Cambridge to protest
the Vietnam War.

00:23:48.730 --> 00:23:51.510
And then come back to this
super-secret facility that was

00:23:51.510 --> 00:23:54.540
working on nuclear guidance and
other things and work on

00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:55.895
the Apollo program.

00:23:55.895 --> 00:23:57.110
And he's this great example.

00:23:57.110 --> 00:23:58.270
And he's still around.

00:23:58.270 --> 00:23:59.560
And he's friend of
mine these days.

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:01.620
And he comes to speak
in my Apollo class.

00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:03.080
And he's actually
a visual artist.

00:24:03.080 --> 00:24:06.090
He does photography downtown.

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:11.470
And of the way that, on the
campus you have this mixture

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:14.500
of different kinds of cultures
and different sorts of

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:18.470
politics, mixing very freely
on the campus.

00:24:18.470 --> 00:24:21.330
And he never found any
problem with that.

00:24:21.330 --> 00:24:24.960
And he did his job just fine.

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:28.030
And he worked at Draper Labs for
another 25 years until he

00:24:28.030 --> 00:24:32.120
retired about 10 years ago.

