And he was vice president of
Grumman when they made the

00:25:25.100 --> 00:25:29.210
Lunar Lander and then became
president of Grumman later.

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:30.730
And these other guys are mostly

00:25:30.730 --> 00:25:32.400
programmers of various kinds.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:35.170
And they mentioned Margaret
Hamilton, one of the very few

00:25:35.170 --> 00:25:38.550
women engineers on
the program.

00:25:38.550 --> 00:25:43.530
Here's the manpower for
hardware, which peaks in '65

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:44.500
and goes down.

00:25:44.500 --> 00:25:48.690
And then the software manpower
just goes right up and almost

00:25:48.690 --> 00:25:50.380
swamps them by the end.

00:25:57.080 --> 00:25:59.315
I'll just say a little bit
more about the landing.

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:07.820
The landing was the most
challenging part

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:09.850
of the entire mission.

00:26:09.850 --> 00:26:13.360
And up until this point right
here, at about 50,000 feet, it

00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:15.590
was entirely controlled
by this computer.

00:26:15.590 --> 00:26:18.700
So all these programmers down
in Cambridge are sitting

00:26:18.700 --> 00:26:20.460
there, watching it on
the big screen.

00:26:20.460 --> 00:26:22.980
And there's a room full of
people like this size.

00:26:22.980 --> 00:26:25.090
And each one of them has a
little piece of that program

00:26:25.090 --> 00:26:26.180
that's written in.

00:26:26.180 --> 00:26:28.680
And they're all sort of
contributing in real time.

00:26:28.680 --> 00:26:31.760
While the astronauts are
standing there monitoring,

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:33.700
until about 500 feet.

00:26:33.700 --> 00:26:37.770
And they have this very clever
thing where the computer would

00:26:37.770 --> 00:26:41.480
spit out a number, which you
could see down here, like 43.

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:44.210
And then the commander, this
would be Neil Armstrong, would

00:26:44.210 --> 00:26:48.000
look through his window at this
number, minus 43, and he

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:51.960
could look out and see where
the target point was.

00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:54.630
And the idea was then he could
change the target point if he

00:26:54.630 --> 00:26:56.190
didn't like where it was.

00:26:56.190 --> 00:27:00.550
And this is another view
of what he might see.

00:27:00.550 --> 00:27:03.820
So there would be that the
landing site there, just sort

00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:06.256
of a passive heads-up display.

00:27:06.256 --> 00:27:09.350
And he could actually jog his
joystick and just say, I don't

00:27:09.350 --> 00:27:10.200
like that landing site.

00:27:10.200 --> 00:27:11.530
I want to kick it over there.

00:27:11.530 --> 00:27:12.700
It would move by a degree.

00:27:12.700 --> 00:27:14.940
And then the computer would
recalculate the entire

00:27:14.940 --> 00:27:16.720
trajectory and bring
them that way.

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:19.830
And he could do that laterally
and fore and aft, as many

00:27:19.830 --> 00:27:22.330
times as he wanted in the
course of the landing.

00:27:22.330 --> 00:27:24.280
And in some of the landings,
they actually did it up to 18

00:27:24.280 --> 00:27:25.430
or 20 times.

00:27:25.430 --> 00:27:27.290
And the idea was it would
gradually converge on a

00:27:27.290 --> 00:27:28.980
perfect spot.

00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:31.920
And the interesting thing about
that, which is sort of

00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:35.650
the topic of another story, is
that on all six landings, they

00:27:35.650 --> 00:27:39.080
turned that system off at about
500 feet and they flew

00:27:39.080 --> 00:27:42.120
it in a more semi-automatic
mode, still

00:27:42.120 --> 00:27:44.580
very much fly by wire.

00:27:44.580 --> 00:27:47.920
But then the story of the Apollo
landings became, the

00:27:47.920 --> 00:27:51.300
astronaut intervenes, turns
off this sort of balky

00:27:51.300 --> 00:27:54.360
technology, which is landing him
in a crater, and saves the

00:27:54.360 --> 00:27:57.260
day by finding the perfect spot
and bringing it down.

00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:00.220
And it was not really an
accurate story because the

00:28:00.220 --> 00:28:03.380
whole system was designed to
interact with the operator to

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:05.680
allow them to select the
right kind of spot.

00:28:05.680 --> 00:28:07.680
But they all turned
it off anyway.

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:10.630
They just wanted to fly.

00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:15.060
Actually Dave Scott, who
is an MIT graduate--

00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:16.910
it's about a third of the people
who walked on the Moon

00:28:16.910 --> 00:28:19.190
had degrees from MIT.

00:28:19.190 --> 00:28:25.250
And I teach a graduate course in
AeroAstro with Larry Young

00:28:25.250 --> 00:28:27.540
on this whole story.

00:28:27.540 --> 00:28:31.560
And we often have the Apollo
astronauts in to

00:28:31.560 --> 00:28:32.390
speak to the students.

00:28:32.390 --> 00:28:34.850
And they'll tell you, they were
either Larry's office

00:28:34.850 --> 00:28:37.410
mates or a few of them were
his master's students when

00:28:37.410 --> 00:28:39.230
they were here in
the early '60s.

00:28:39.230 --> 00:28:41.280
And actually tomorrow, Dave
Scott is going to come.

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:44.160
He was the commander
of Apollo 15.

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:46.420
And he's the only one who I
think gave a really accurate

00:28:46.420 --> 00:28:48.290
description of what happened
in these last seconds.

00:28:48.290 --> 00:28:52.790
He said, you can say that you
wanted to be in the loop if

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:53.670
anything went wrong.

00:28:53.670 --> 00:28:55.490
But you knew that if something
went wrong with a computer,

00:28:55.490 --> 00:28:57.680
you were dead anyway.

00:28:57.680 --> 00:28:59.210
But I came away that whole
way and darn it, I

00:28:59.210 --> 00:29:00.480
just wanted to fly.

00:29:00.480 --> 00:29:04.600
And so they all ended
up flying it the

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:06.310
last 500 feet or so.

00:29:06.310 --> 00:29:10.260
And then NASA and the public
and the press could all say

00:29:10.260 --> 00:29:18.610
that sort of traditional
American values were confirmed

00:29:18.610 --> 00:29:21.190
by these sort of cowboy
astronauts landing on the Moon

00:29:21.190 --> 00:29:21.870
by themselves.

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:25.280
But actually there was this
MIT-designed computer there.

00:29:25.280 --> 00:29:27.960
And it's an interesting story
too about MIT educations,

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:31.700
because the earlier crews--

00:29:31.700 --> 00:29:35.480
Aldren had a Ph.D. from MIT.

00:29:35.480 --> 00:29:38.680
And the earlier astronauts
were not

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:40.310
very academic engineers.

00:29:40.310 --> 00:29:43.880
But gradually over
time, they became

00:29:43.880 --> 00:29:45.440
much more highly educated.

00:29:45.440 --> 00:29:48.700
And MIT, with the exception of
West Point and the Naval

00:29:48.700 --> 00:29:51.930
Academy and Air Force Academy,
the service academies, MIT has

00:29:51.930 --> 00:29:54.660
trained more astronauts
than any other school.

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:59.150
And it became increasingly sort
of de rigeur to have a

00:29:59.150 --> 00:30:01.380
master's or a Ph.D
in engineering.

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:05.290
And those crews were much more
accepting of these advanced

00:30:05.290 --> 00:30:07.810
techniques for the guidance and
much less interested in

00:30:07.810 --> 00:30:10.270
just flying it on in
by themselves.

00:30:10.270 --> 00:30:12.400
Alan Shepard, and we mentioned
his flight, he

00:30:12.400 --> 00:30:13.650
commanded Apollo 14.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:19.750
And he said, aah, if the
computer failed, I could have

00:30:19.750 --> 00:30:22.990
just taken over and landed
by myself on the Moon.

00:30:22.990 --> 00:30:25.750
Which is physically impossible,
because you're

00:30:25.750 --> 00:30:30.090
looking at a terrain landscape
that has zero indicators of

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:31.690
how far away from it you are.

00:30:31.690 --> 00:30:33.950
You could actually be six inches
or six miles and you

00:30:33.950 --> 00:30:35.330
wouldn't be able to tell the
difference because there's no

00:30:35.330 --> 00:30:40.480
trees, there's no trucks,
there are no highways,

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:42.640
anything to give you
a sense of scale.

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:47.295
And he had a problem with
his landing radar.

00:30:47.295 --> 00:30:49.300
It didn't come in until
the last few minutes.

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:52.330
But if the landing radar had
never come in, he said he

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:53.380
would have landed it anyway.

00:30:53.380 --> 00:30:55.175
And he probably would
have crashed, if he

00:30:55.175 --> 00:30:56.990
had tried to do that.

00:30:56.990 --> 00:30:58.710
They're actually using this--

00:30:58.710 --> 00:31:01.010
anybody want to guess
what this is, what

00:31:01.010 --> 00:31:02.260
this diagram portrays?

00:31:05.170 --> 00:31:08.140
It's actually a model of
the lunar terrain.

00:31:08.140 --> 00:31:10.506
So if you've ever programmed a
control system-- we used to

00:31:10.506 --> 00:31:13.680
have this problem building
underwater robots all time--

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:17.040
and you want to hold
a fixed altitude.

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:19.170
If you're cruising along the
bottom of the ocean in a robot

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:21.320
that's programmed to hold a
fixed altitude, so it's

00:31:21.320 --> 00:31:24.270
sending a sonar beam off the
bottom and trying to hold an

00:31:24.270 --> 00:31:27.940
altitude, and then you go over
a hole, the vehicle is going

00:31:27.940 --> 00:31:29.440
to dive down like this
and smash into

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:31.720
the side of the hole.

00:31:31.720 --> 00:31:33.360
And same thing here.

00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:36.640
If you're trying to fly over
a mountain range--

00:31:36.640 --> 00:31:39.940
it's not a coincidence that
the site for the Apollo 11

00:31:39.940 --> 00:31:41.760
landing was called the
Sea of Tranquility.

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:45.070
They found the flattest, most
even terrain they could find.

00:31:45.070 --> 00:31:47.270
But the geologists who were
running the science

00:31:47.270 --> 00:31:50.220
experiments, really wanted to go
into places where there was

00:31:50.220 --> 00:31:52.190
a lot of geological activity,
so the terrain

00:31:52.190 --> 00:31:54.690
was a lot more crazy.

00:31:54.690 --> 00:31:58.360
And on the later flights, they
really did land very much high

00:31:58.360 --> 00:31:59.560
up in the mountains.

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:03.450
And this is just a way, where
with five line segments, in a

00:32:03.450 --> 00:32:07.310
very, very simple computer
model, all it takes is these

00:32:07.310 --> 00:32:11.770
five line segments and like six
numbers, you could model

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:12.960
that there were mountains
here.

00:32:12.960 --> 00:32:15.440
And then you expected the
terrain to go like that.

00:32:15.440 --> 00:32:18.060
And the computer model could eat
all that stuff for lunch

00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:20.300
and it would keep a very stable
trajectory and allow

00:32:20.300 --> 00:32:23.030
you to go over the mountains,
and then land right at the

00:32:23.030 --> 00:32:26.820
edge, which is what they did on
Apollo 15, and 16, and 17,

00:32:26.820 --> 00:32:28.130
a very clever thing.

00:32:31.520 --> 00:32:34.930
That's the view out the window,
of Aldrin's side.

00:32:34.930 --> 00:32:38.750
AUDIENCE: When do you begin to
see the sort of the decline in

00:32:38.750 --> 00:32:44.570
the pilot-orientedness
of the astronauts

00:32:44.570 --> 00:32:47.230
wanting to control more?

00:32:47.230 --> 00:32:51.070
Because the thing that your
lecture brings to my mind is

00:32:51.070 --> 00:32:54.320
the book, The Right Stuff, in
which that's a big issue.

00:32:54.320 --> 00:32:58.880
But clearly what you're saying
is over time, that declines.

00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:01.900
PROFESSOR: Hopefully,
we're seeing it now.

00:33:01.900 --> 00:33:03.280
After the Moon landing,
what did they do?

00:33:03.280 --> 00:33:06.240
They started sending an
airplane into orbit.

00:33:06.240 --> 00:33:08.020
It wasn't the wisest choice.

00:33:08.020 --> 00:33:10.540
But it was because the
astronauts wanted to fly

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:12.860
something that had
wings on it.

00:33:12.860 --> 00:33:15.310
And it's not a very efficient
way to go to and from space.

00:33:19.150 --> 00:33:21.890
AUDIENCE: So was Alex Roland
right all along?

00:33:21.890 --> 00:33:24.140
PROFESSOR: Yeah, in some way.

00:33:24.140 --> 00:33:28.060
But from MIT's point of view,
again building into the Bill

00:33:28.060 --> 00:33:34.720
Leslie piece from today, the
Apollo program ends in 1972.

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:37.230
It has this huge triumph
in 1969.

00:33:37.230 --> 00:33:40.000
And that's right when all
these protests end up

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:43.050
happening and the Draper
Labs gets spun out.

00:33:43.050 --> 00:33:45.840
They were extremely offended
and insulted by that move.

00:33:45.840 --> 00:33:49.310
And there is still hard feelings
about it today.

00:33:49.310 --> 00:33:52.950
A lot of the people who worked
at the Instrumentation Lab

00:33:52.950 --> 00:33:55.050
were happy to work on
a civilian project.

00:33:55.050 --> 00:33:57.660
And one of the reasons they
liked working on Apollo was

00:33:57.660 --> 00:34:00.410
that it was a non-weapons
kind of project.

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:03.240
And then they felt like they
got the bad end of the rap

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:04.690
during a lot of the
protests anyway.

00:34:04.690 --> 00:34:06.710
There was still a lot of
military funding and a lot of

00:34:06.710 --> 00:34:10.139
weapons work going on there.

00:34:10.139 --> 00:34:14.590
But it's sort of this irony of
this moment when this part of

00:34:14.590 --> 00:34:20.159
MIT has this world shattering
technological triumph in a

00:34:20.159 --> 00:34:23.580
way, and then also becomes
the brunt of it.

00:34:23.580 --> 00:34:26.210
And it just shows you again the
ways that all these things

00:34:26.210 --> 00:34:27.870
on this campus and in
the country were

00:34:27.870 --> 00:34:29.159
conflicted at the time.

00:34:29.159 --> 00:34:33.530
And somebody wrote recently
that at the time it seemed

00:34:33.530 --> 00:34:36.060
like the hippies and the Moon
landings were the furthest

00:34:36.060 --> 00:34:36.650
thing apart.

00:34:36.650 --> 00:34:39.690
One of them was the military
industrial complex and one of

00:34:39.690 --> 00:34:42.400
them was this kind of Utopian
vision of the world.

00:34:42.400 --> 00:34:45.030
But looking back 30 years later,
you can see they have a

00:34:45.030 --> 00:34:45.690
lot in common.

00:34:45.690 --> 00:34:48.469
They were both sort of Utopian,
futuristic visions

00:34:48.469 --> 00:34:52.239
that never quite succeeded in
the promise that they held.

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:55.210
And yet they both influenced
the world in different ways

00:34:55.210 --> 00:34:57.139
that people hadn't
really expected.

00:34:57.139 --> 00:34:58.460
And that was true on campus.

00:34:58.460 --> 00:35:01.170
So mentioned in their response
paper, I'm forgetting who,

00:35:01.170 --> 00:35:08.310
about how it was really the
one moment there was major

00:35:08.310 --> 00:35:09.930
political activism on campus.

00:35:09.930 --> 00:35:11.060
There were other places too.

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:15.100
But in this entire story, we
were teaching you the history

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:19.670
of Yale University or
NYU or Columbia.

00:35:19.670 --> 00:35:22.280
It's a very political story
the way the students are

00:35:22.280 --> 00:35:25.600
responding to the currents in
the outside world and how

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:26.900
those things played
out on campus.

00:35:26.900 --> 00:35:30.870
And it's a much more muted story
here for reasons that

00:35:30.870 --> 00:35:31.890
might be worth discussing.

00:35:31.890 --> 00:35:35.740
And in the discussion, it's
really remarkable and notable

00:35:35.740 --> 00:35:39.700
this one moment in the '70s,
when it happened.

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:45.455
And whereas, I went to college
at Yale in the '80s and there

00:35:45.455 --> 00:35:49.080
were students being arrested all
the time for protests and

00:35:49.080 --> 00:35:51.470
occupying the president's
office and things.

00:35:51.470 --> 00:35:55.680
It became almost a kind of
a cartoon of itself,

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:58.040
it happened so often.

00:35:58.040 --> 00:36:04.400
Well, if you noticed in the
150th Exhibit, one of the 150

00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:07.960
objects is a tape of the
Grateful Dead playing on the

00:36:07.960 --> 00:36:09.710
front steps of the
student center.

00:36:09.710 --> 00:36:13.390
And I think it was April 1970,
was that when Kent State was?

00:36:13.390 --> 00:36:17.010
And the thing they write about
it, it was within a week after

00:36:17.010 --> 00:36:18.940
Kent State.

00:36:18.940 --> 00:36:21.130
And the campus was
extremely tense.

00:36:21.130 --> 00:36:23.540
Everybody was very unsure what
was going to happen.

00:36:23.540 --> 00:36:26.360
And when they played their
music, they were very aware of

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:29.240
that and really tried to make
it be a sort of soothing,

00:36:29.240 --> 00:36:34.980
calming moment as opposed to
a fractious, contentious,

00:36:34.980 --> 00:36:36.360
potentially violent moment.

00:36:36.360 --> 00:36:39.080
And that's one of the reasons
Debbie chose it as part of the

00:36:39.080 --> 00:36:40.330
150 objects.

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:44.930
AUDIENCE: Very interesting.

00:36:44.930 --> 00:36:48.040
PROFESSOR: So that takes
us up to 1970 or so.

00:36:48.040 --> 00:36:51.220
And then there's four more
decades to deal with, between

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:53.360
now and then, some of
which we read about.

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:58.670
The Cambridge recombinant DNA
story is in some ways very

00:36:58.670 --> 00:37:01.200
much a continuation of
this sort of story.

00:37:01.200 --> 00:37:04.113
Cambridge was, I'm not sure how
much it still is, it still

00:37:04.113 --> 00:37:07.280
is a little bit, a very
left-leaning community outside

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:11.520
of the university, very
activist, very concerned about

00:37:11.520 --> 00:37:14.900
these big, potentially
scary technologies.

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:19.730
That was very much the mood of
the time, was what is this big

00:37:19.730 --> 00:37:22.670
nasty force of technology
doing to our world?

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:24.900
And MIT, it was pretty
easy for to become

00:37:24.900 --> 00:37:26.460
the center of that.

00:37:26.460 --> 00:37:30.040
And John Durant's piece shows
you how that played out,

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:35.950
arguably in a constructive way,
a very interesting one.

00:37:35.950 --> 00:37:38.140
And then in '80s,
the military--

00:37:38.140 --> 00:37:40.940
we talked about this a little
bit last time--

00:37:40.940 --> 00:37:43.100
got very much going again
under Reagan.

00:37:43.100 --> 00:37:47.060
And a lot of money came into
computer science and other

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:49.250
engineering disciplines.

00:37:49.250 --> 00:37:53.840
But also the economics of
technology and the challenge

00:37:53.840 --> 00:37:55.470
from Japan became a big issue.

00:37:55.470 --> 00:37:57.490
That had a lot of influence
on campus.

00:37:57.490 --> 00:38:01.480
All the while, biotech and
biology is sort of creeping up

00:38:01.480 --> 00:38:06.138
in importance and
dollar value.

00:38:06.138 --> 00:38:09.040
And then the Cold War ends.

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:13.840
Chuck Vest becomes president in
the late either '89 or '90,

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:15.590
'91 I think.

00:38:15.590 --> 00:38:17.660
He became president right about
when I came here as a

00:38:17.660 --> 00:38:18.930
grad student.

00:38:18.930 --> 00:38:21.550
And the big question on
everybody's mind was what at

00:38:21.550 --> 00:38:22.800
that point?

00:38:26.990 --> 00:38:29.690
MIT is dependent on government
funding for so long.

00:38:29.690 --> 00:38:32.720
Now that the Cold War is over,
are we going to just shrivel

00:38:32.720 --> 00:38:34.140
up and die?

00:38:34.140 --> 00:38:36.600
And the pendulum goes again.

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:39.010
Where do they go?

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:40.210
Back towards industry.

00:38:40.210 --> 00:38:41.980
And the '90s is very much--

00:38:41.980 --> 00:38:44.100
I mean the government research
support is always there, but

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.040
very much industry.

00:38:50.030 --> 00:38:52.240
I remember Chuck Vest saying--
it was probably pretty late in

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:54.950
his presidency, soon before he
stepped down, in a faculty

00:38:54.950 --> 00:38:58.030
meeting, I've spent so many
years cultivating industrial

00:38:58.030 --> 00:38:59.830
sponsors, it's very difficult.

00:38:59.830 --> 00:39:01.320
It's very time consuming.

00:39:01.320 --> 00:39:03.570
I would be very happy for the
government to start up again

00:39:03.570 --> 00:39:04.350
and support--

00:39:04.350 --> 00:39:07.770
I mean it didn't go down
ever, as much as

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:09.460
people feared it did.

00:39:09.460 --> 00:39:14.890
But it became less of a
percentage of MIT's income.

00:39:14.890 --> 00:39:18.480
Then the financial crisis in '08
happens and the stimulus

00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:20.890
package comes in,
more government.

00:39:20.890 --> 00:39:23.980
And the government runs out
of money, less government.

00:39:23.980 --> 00:39:25.770
So this pendulum
keeps swinging.

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:30.440
AUDIENCE: The periods
are shorter.

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:31.710
PROFESSOR: The periods
are maybe shorter.

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:32.960
It could be true.

